<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / International Bonds: Indigestion may follow Kingdom of
Sweden's issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRIAN BOLLEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Kingdom of Sweden yesterday became the second Scandinavian borrower in
as many days to look to the bond markets for Dollars 2bn. However, its
three-year issue was compared unfavourably with Finland's five-year global
bonds launched the day before.
Some traders complained about the amount, the maturity and the borrowing
instrument although they did agree, largely, that the pricing looked just
about right.
Such a large amount could, however, take some time to digest, particularly
in the light of Finland's success.
After a series of deals in D-Marks, French francs and sterling over five
years, Sweden's decision to diversify its maturities with a big liquid
current coupon benchmark deal in the three-year range was not totally
vindicated. Joint lead manager and book runner J. P. Morgan confirmed that
while demand was good the issue did not sell out.
As Sweden's increased Dollars 5bn SEC shelf registration in New York is now
effective, some traders thought it odd the kingdom should launch such a
large Eurobond rather than try a global issue.
But Credit Suisse First Boston, the other lead manager, said that one of the
main attractions of the Eurobond market remained the ability to launch such
a large deal at very short notice.
The bonds bring the total raised on the capital markets under the second
phase of the kingdom's emergency borrowing programme to around Ecu6.5bn,
said Mr Staffan Crona, director-general of the Swedish National Debt Office.
This leaves a further Ecu8.5bn to be raised.
Finland's global issue, priced yesterday at the bottom of its indicated
range to yield 82 basis points over Treasuries, was still generating
excitement and comment. It vindicates the global issue concept for big
issues, say some traders.
Finland has got a better deal than anyone thought possible a few weeks ago,
and set itself up to tap residual demand in the US next year where investors
could well be persuaded to buy more at longer maturities.
Elsewhere, SudWestLB took advantage of the continuing demand for
high-quality current coupon Eurosterling paper with its Pounds 100m 10-year
8 5/8 per cent subordinated bond.
The implicit state guarantee enjoyed by German borrowers such as SudWestLB
means that in effect they cannot go bankrupt and can launch subordinated
debt at a very tight spread to gilts.
Lead manager Lehman Brothers said it had identified a particular lack of
supply of triple-A rated bonds in the 10-year range, and that the issue
traded around the reoffer spread after it broke syndicate.
In the equity-related sector, Square D's discounted convertible issue
provides Schneider, its French parent, with low-cost funds to refinance
Dollars 150m of a seven-year term loan it raised to help buy Square D in
1991.
Ireland is being talked about as a potential borrower of Dollars
300m-Dollars 500m over five years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
