<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / International Company News: Fiat in top management shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIAT yesterday announced a streamlining of top management, splitting the
organisation into two broad sectors - industry and industrial development,
and financial control and resource management.
The aim is to prepare Fiat, Italy's largest private industrial conglomerate,
for lean times and costly investment in its main business, the motor
industry, as well as organise the divestiture of non-core activities.
The shake-up comes as Fiat prepares for the departure of chairman Mr Gianni
Agnelli who is due to hand over to his brother, Umberto, in 1994.
The new structure paves the way for the departure of Mr Cesare Romiti as the
chief executive officer, who is thought unlikely to remain after 1994.
The very obvious promotion in the reorganisation of Mr Giorgio Garuzzo, the
54-year-old chief operating officer, puts him in line for Mr Romiti's job.
Mr Garuzzo's role in the group is to be substantially expanded. He is being
put in charge of one of the two broad divisions of the new management - the
automotive industry, Fiat's diversified industrial portfolio and industrial
development. The second broad division in charge of the group's financial
control has been given to Mr Paolo Mattioli with the creation of the post of
chief financial officer.
A Fiat spokesman said the new structure would be effective from December 1.
There is no direct reference to redundancies at the head office in Turin
where more than 1,000 managerial staff are employed. However, tertiary
activities such as legal services, travel and property, would be conducted
elsewhere.
Fiat's move follows a similar shake-up by Olivetti last week. The group
relies on the motor sector for more than two thirds of turnover and Fiat's
profits are being squeezed (first-half 1992 profits fell to L655bn) by the
recession in its main markets.
It is pledged to invest some L40,000bn (Dollars 29bn) over the next decade
in the motor sector alone. Already this year it has closed a Lancia plant
near Turin but more widespread cuts could follow.
In recent weeks speculation has mounted that Fiat has been studying possible
disposals, notably its profitable store chain, Rinascente, as well as other
sell-offs including Cogefar Impresit, Italy's largest private construction
group, and its Toro insurance business.
The sale of non-essential assets is likely to be one of the main tasks of
the new chief financial officer.
</TEXT>
