FT  18 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Nestle paid Pounds 30m to take over Clarke
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nestle, the Swiss-owned food group, is believed to have paid slightly more
than Pounds 30m for the majority of the assets and goodwill of Clarke Foods,
Britain's second-largest ice-cream manufacturer which went into receivership
last month.
The deal means that trade creditors might salvage as much as 50p in the
pound. Clarke had debts of about Pounds 25m.
Nestle is not believed to have taken on Clarke's debts, although it is
understood to have reached an agreement over the Pounds 6m Clarke owed to
Alfa-Laval.
The Swedish company supplied about Pounds 12m-worth of equipment to the
ice-cream manufacturer after Clarke's purchase and relaunch of the Lyons
Maid brand. Delays in the installation of this equipment meant Clarke was
unable to manufacture ice-cream in time for the hottest months of the
summer. It lost many retail outlets as a result.
The Nestle bid beat an indirect attempt by Mars to gain the Clarke business.
</TEXT>
