<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Shareholders in ITN given new outline on ownership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POSSIBLE future of Independent Television News was outlined in a
three-part offer sent to shareholders yesterday.
The improved offer from Mr Michael Green, chairman of Carlton Communications
who is leading a consortium to take over the organisation, would mean:
around Pounds 13 a share for the three shareholders that have lost their
franchises - Thames Television, Television South and Television South West.
The original offer was Pounds 1 a share;
membership of the consortium which is now made up of Carlton, Central,
London Weekend and Reuters would be extended to include Granada Television,
Scottish and Anglia. The original consortium members and Granada would each
have 18 per cent and the other two would have 5 per cent each;
the other ITV companies, which would no longer be shareholders, would get a
smoothing out of the five-year news supply agreement set to average Pounds
53.3m a year over five years.
The improved package does not come in time to stop the extended offer
lapsing today.
There is also growing concern that shareholders have not seen promised
revisions to a shareholder agreement.
There are fears about whether the four original consortium members are
acting in concert, how much freedom of action ITN executive directors would
have and whether new guarantees of editorial independence are required.
If the revised deal is nailed down, a US network, possibly ABC, could join
the consortium at a later date.
</TEXT>
