<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Lithuanian poll winner will preserve links with Russia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VILNIUS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE newly elected Lithuanian leader said yesterday that he would continue to
encourage western investment but promised to safeguard economic links with
Russia.
Mr Algirdas Brazauskas, leader of the former Communists who this week won
the general election, said in an interview with the Financial Times that he
had built strong links with the centrist Russian Civic Union bloc now
bidding for power in Moscow. These forces were likely soon to prevail in
Russia, said Mr Brazauskas, whose Democratic Labour party won an absolute
majority in Lithuania's parliament.
Russia and the other former Soviet republics still provide most of
Lithuania's supplies and take the majority of its output.
'The former government said everything would come from the west - but where
is it? They said we would get western investment. I don't see it,' he said.
Mr Brazauskas is thought to prefer a gentler course towards a market economy
than western-style shock therapy. His views accord with the criticism voiced
about the Russian government by General Alexander Rutskoi, Russian
vice-president, and Mr Arkady Volsky, head of the Russian Union of
Industrialists.
The election winner, however, reiterated his belief in market reforms. 'We
will continue our agreements with the International Monetary Fund, but they
must understand that one-third of the people live in poverty and that we may
be on the verge of hunger in some areas,' he said.
Mr Brazauskas, 60, said he would delay holding a presidential election for
at least six months after his party takes power pending discussions with
political parties and the passing of an electoral law.
He will be chairman of the parliament - as was President Vytautas
Landsbergis whose Sajudis nationalist movement lost Sunday's poll - but he
did not say whether he would run for the presidency.
He reiterated that his party would now be social democratic and not
communist.
Russian economic crisis, Page 3
</TEXT>
