<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Observer: PM in bank note scandal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Paul Keating is the first Australian prime minister for years who can safely
be cleared of debasing the currency - inflation has fallen to less than 0.8
per cent since he took over from Bob Hawke just under a year ago.
But defacing it is a different matter, and the federal police think they may
be able to finger him on that score.
The alleged crime was perpetrated during a walkabout in North Queensland
when Keating unwisely signed two ADollars 5 notes at the request of a local
artist. Now the artist is selling the notes for ADollars 3,000 each, and the
premier is being investigated under the Crimes (Currency) Act, which
provides for imprisonment of up to two years.
If the case ever got to court, it could even cost the prime minister his
job. Justice minister Michael Tate has promised that the case would be dealt
with impartially.
Keating plays down the incident as summer nonsense. But there is some
evidence that it was as much a political statement as a vote-catching
exercise. The notes he signed were examples of the freshly issued ADollars 5
note carrying the Queen's portrait in place of the 19th century pioneer
pictured on the earlier design.
Keating was one of many republican Australians who unsuccessfully tried to
persuade the Reserve Bank to cancel the issue.
</TEXT>
