FT  18 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some of the best arts programmes of recent years have come out of BBC2's
Bookmark (8.10). The series returns today with an account of the English
Shakespeare Company's tour of Malawi with 'Macbeth'. Producer John Purdie
says 'Despite the language problems, Malawian audiences are weaned on an
oral story-telling tradition and live in a world where witchcraft and power
politics are daily realities. They quickly identify the plot of the Scottish
tragedy and relish the obvious parallels between Shakespeare's characters
and their own political leaders'.
Dispatches sounds like yet another of those occasions when programme makers
climb on their high horse and flay the powers-that-be for spending too
little on hospital care. What broadcasters never do is state where they
would draw the line, given that there would be no great difficulty in the
modern world of expensive high-tech medicine in spending the entire GNP on
health care (9.00 C4).
BBC2 begins Nice Town, a three-part drama in which Paul McGann and Philip
Davis play brothers one of whom decides to become a secret sperm donor for
the other's wife (9.25).
