<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Maverick Clark is used to speaking
his mind
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALAN Clark, the former defence and trade minister who last night was at
the centre of the arms-to-Iraq controversy, is used to being cast as a
maverick.
In government he was not afraid to speak his mind - sometimes to the alarm
of senior ministers.
Mr Clark, 64, is a rich, unpredictable and sardonic man who lives in a
castle. When asked for his comment on the Crown Prosecution Service's
decision to ask for an inquiry into his Matrix Churchill trail evidence, he
replied in typical brashness: 'Haven't got any.'
The government is aware that, should more be uncovered in the arms-to-Iraq
affair, it could become harder to distance the role of Mr Clark from
ministers still in office.
He was a trade and industry minister from 1986 to 1989, during the ceasefire
in the Iraq/Iran war.
Although it is now clear from documents in the Matrix Churchill trial that
the government was re-interpreting the guidelines on exports to both
countries, Mr Clark told parliament in April 1989 that there were 'no plans
to change the current restrictions on the export of arms to Iraq which
impose an embargo on the export of lethal equipment.'
He added: 'The guidelines are kept under review in the light of developments
in the situation there.'
Mr Clark dropped a bombshell in court earlier this month by admitting he
advised Matrix Churchill and other British toolmakers to draw up
specifications emphasising peaceful rather than military applications.
The court heard this evidence was 'inconsistent' with his earlier statements
to Customs and Excise investigators. It led to an admission by Customs that
it could no longer sustain a case against three former directors of the
Coventry machine-tool maker.
Discussing his advice to the machine tool-makers in court, Mr Clark said it
involved 'our old friend economical.'
'Economical with the truth?', Mr Geoffrey Robertson, QC for one of the
directors responded. 'With the actualite',' Mr Clark replied. He said it was
not misleading or dishonest to have made such a suggestion and did not
amount to a tip-off. It was a case of 'Whitehall cosmetics' to keep the
records ambiguous.
He denied he showed companies how best to circumvent government guidelines
on arms exports to Iraq, but said he thought the government's guidelines
were 'tiresome and intrusive'. He added it was in Britain's best interests
for the Iran-Iraq war to continue as long as possible.
It was not the only occasion in which he has been disarmingly frank. Last
year, in the New Statesman magazine, he nominated 'Love in the time of
Cholera' as his favourite book of the year because: 'For anyone who has been
in love. . . this is the book. . . It illustrates the utter dominance of the
female.'
In his last comments in the Commons before retiring from politics at the
general election, Mr Clark admitted to MPs that 'I have had idiosyncratic,
some would say tendentious, moments of behaviour which have always been
treated with great tolerance by the House'.
</TEXT>
