<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Portillo rules out private pay curb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has no intention of imposing an incomes policy on the private
sector, Mr Michael Portillo, the chief secretary to the Treasury, said
yesterday.
However, in evidence to the Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee, he
said the government had a right to point out the danger of high pay
settlements in the environment caused by sterling's devaluation since the
pound left the European exchange rate mechanism on September 16.
Answering questions from Mr Nicholas Budgen, (Cons, Wolverhampton South
West), Mr Portillo said past British devaluations had not produced the
economic benefits people thought they might produce.
He said British industry had granted its employees high real wage increases
instead of winning increased orders.
Speaking on the day after Mr John Major's Guildhall speech in which the
prime minister urged business leaders to control executive pay, Mr Portillo
said the government would not restrain private industry in its pay policies
and had no intention of imposing its will on the private sector.
Nevertheless, it could make statements of a 'broader sort' about pay, he
said.
Mr Portillo made clear that the government's position on public sector pay
was quite different.
One reason for its plan to limit pay settlements in the public sector to a
maximum of 1.5 per cent was to resist cost pressures and so offer better
services to business and the general public.
In wide-ranging testimony, Mr Portillo provided an explanation for the sharp
Pounds 1.16bn fall in payments to the European Community envisaged in the
government's spending plans for 1993-94.
The cut from earlier planned levels reflected:
A reduced forecast for EC spending on agriculture.
Expectations of substantially higher receipts from the farm guarantee fund
following reform of the EC's common agricultural policy. A lower UK share of
gross contributions to the Community reflecting a lower UK share of EC gross
domestic product.
</TEXT>
