<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Lamont pressure wins broad support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL BUSINESSES gave widespread support yesterday to Mr Norman Lamont's
call for banks to pass on recent interest-rate reductions fully and promptly
to help them survive the recession.
But while businesses said almost unanimously that small companies were
having to wait too long for their interest rate cuts, the chancellor's plea
has also revived wider concerns about the banks' attitude.
For some, it is inevitable that the banks will try to delay the good news
for small companies - their bigger clients have more bargaining power and
can shop around for loans.
For others, what one company yesterday said was the banks' 'unsupportive
attitude to anything involving risk' is far more dangerous than delay in
reducing interest rates.
But not everyone agrees that the banks are playing unfairly. The Forum for
Private Business, which represents more than 20,000 companies, says
accusations that banks have failed to pass on interest-rate cuts are false
and distract attention from the real issue of improving bank services.
Mr Stan Mendham, the founder of the Business Forum, said: 'To cry wolf over
allegations which we know cannot be substantiated would degrade our future
task of ensuring that the banks play their role in ensuring a
small-business-led recovery.'
The Confederation of British Industry commented: 'It is still unclear the
extent to which banks have or have not passed on the benefits of lower
interest rates.'
It is hard to find a good word from industry for the banks. The Specialist
Engineering Contractors' Group, which represents more than 3,800 mechanical
and electrical contractors, will be campaigning on interest rates and other
bank-related issues.
Mr Terry Cann, the group's head of marketing, said: 'On a number of
occasions different members have spoken discouragingly about the level of
support from the banks.' Yesterday Mr Cann took a call from a member
incensed by having to continue to pay more interest than he had expected.
The Federation of Small Businesses, representing more than 60,000 companies,
has written to the chairmen of the four largest clearing banks asking them
to ensure that interest-rate reductions are passed on to its members.
Mr John Harris, federation president, is particularly critical of National
Westminster Bank and of Barclays, which sets a minimum rate for some
overdrafts to small companies.
A letter from National Westminster offering an overdraft facility for Pounds
8,000 to a management training company in October stated: 'Interest will be
charged at a rate equal to the base rate from time to time plus 6 1/2 per
cent per annum subject to a minimum rate of 14.5 per cent per annum.'
National Westminster said last night that it had reduced its minimum lending
rates last week. 'This customer will have reaped the full benefit of last
week's base-rate reduction,' the bank said. A more widespread criticism was
that banks used the reduction in base rates to widen the margin charged on
loans.
'Some of our members, when interest rates previously were reduced by one
percentage point, received letters almost the same day announcing that the
margin charged on their loans was going up by the same amount,' Mr Harris
said.
Mr Stephen Crampton, managing director of London-based 3D Scanners, expects
sales to double every year for its unique 3D digitising service  - turning
solid objects into a computer-aided design model.
But he said the company recently risked failing when its bank refused to
renew a loan at very short notice.
Meanwhile, the bulk of the company's medium-term borrowings are through the
government-insured small business loan guarantee scheme.
'What is clear,' the CBI said, 'is that there is great dissatisfaction at
the way in which banks levy their charges. It is not always apparent how
banks arrive at the additional charges over base rates they make.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
