<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Government borrowed Pounds 1.78bn last month
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT borrowing totalled Pounds 1.78bn last month, making it the first
October since 1984 in which there has been no net repayment of government
debt.
The figure reflected high government expenditure and weak tax revenues
resulting from the recession, and was in line with the Treasury's latest
forecast for a public sector borrowing requirement of Pounds 37bn this
financial year.
Last month's total, announced by the Central Statistical Office yesterday,
represented a significant deterioration in public sector finances. There
were net repayments of Pounds 0.6bn in October last year and Pounds 2.4bn in
October 1990.
The cumulative total of government borrowing this year reached Pounds 20.2bn
including privatisation proceeds. That compares with a cumulative total of
only Pounds 8.7bn in the first seven months of the financial year 1991-92.
However, ministers have made clear that the government is experiencing no
problems funding this year's greatly increased PSBR and has no intention of
abandoning its policy of fully funding the deficit. Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, told the Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee this week
that the PSBR had been overfunded this year, largely because of the effects
of supporting sterling in September.
He said the government would act to compensate for this overfunding over the
rest of 1992-93, indicating that it would slow down gilts sales.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, told the committee
yesterday that the chancellor's intention 'on the whole' was not to make
foreign currency borrowing a feature of the government's funding policy.
Proceeds from privatisation were negligible last month. In the first seven
months of the present financial year they amounted to Pounds 5bn, taking the
cumulative PSBR excluding privatisation proceeds to Pounds 25.2bn. The high
figure came as little surprise to the markets. Many observers had been
expecting a poor figure following the big revision to the Treasury forecast
in last week's Autumn Statement.
Mr Lamont disclosed how badly government finances were hit when he revised
the PSBR forecast for this financial year from Pounds 28.1bn - as forecast
in the Budget - to Pounds 37bn. The Treasury estimates that government
borrowing in 1993-94 will rise to Pounds 44bn, although many City economists
consider that optimistic.
'I think that in the absence of any massive increases in taxation and
drastic cuts in expenditure, the PSBR is going to be a headache for this
government for the rest of this decade,' said Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief
economist at Citibank.
</TEXT>
