<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 92 / Executive salary rises 'slowing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXECUTIVE pay increases have slowed by 50 per cent over the past 12 months,
approaching the same level of increases as other employees, according to
data from the Monks Partnership, executive pay analysts.
But Mr John Major's appeal for pay restraint in the boardroom was not
welcomed by Lord King, British Airways chairman and one of the UK's
highest-paid chairmen, who said top businessmen needed competitive salaries
to reflect productivity.
Lord King said: 'I think we should be careful about going back to the awful
mistakes of the Heath days. We must have the freedom to run our companies,
and if we want to attract talent we have to be able to pay for it.'
Other industrialists welcomed Mr Major's call, which was made at the Lord
Mayor's Banquet on Tuesday night.
The latest estimates from Monks' clients suggest that directors and senior
managers will this year receive basic increases of about 4 per cent, down
from the 5 per cent to 6 per cent predicted in July. Monks calculates that
directors and senior managers last year received basic rises of about 8 per
cent.
However, the latest signals emerging from the private sector are mixed, in
spite of government calls to follow its public-sector pay limit of 1.5 per
cent.
National Power, the privatised electricity generator, has approved a basic
pay rise of 3.95 per cent for about 9,000 staff, most of whom also received
a Pounds 2,000 lump-sum payment for accepting a new deal on preformance pay
and flexible working hours.
The main industrial unions support the deal, meaning it is almost certain to
be accepted. Mr Doug Rooney, of the AEEU electricians' and engineering
workers' union, said the performance element was unusual for industrial
workers.
Meanwhile, several GEC subsidiaries have imposed pay freezes, including GPT,
the telecommunications group, and GEC-Ferranti. Others, including the
Anglo-French engineering group GEC Alsthom, have awarded small pay rises.
The TUC public services committee met yesterday to co-ordinate opposition to
the government's 1.5 per cent limit for the public sector, but few union
officials predict industrial unrest. The TUC wants to meet the prime
minister over the matter. Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe, leader of the public
service union Nupe, did not rule out strike action.
</TEXT>
