   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria's handover to civilian rule has been postponed from next January to
August 27, President Ibrahim Babangida announced last night, writes Michael
Holman.
Last month the military government nullified the results of presidential
primaries, marred by widespread electoral fraud, and sacked the executives
of the country's two permitted parties. President Babangida, speaking in the
federal capital of Abuja, said that the 23 presidential candidates who ran
in the primaries would be disqualified from contesting the presidential
election now set for June 12.
The government is now expected to redouble efforts to renew a lapsed
stand-by agreement with the IMF. Negotiations have been affected by
uncertainty over the hand-over timetable. An agreement is an essential
precondition to further rescheduling of Nigeria's Dollars 30bn external
debt.
