FT  18 NOV 92 / S African interest rates cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE South African Reserve Bank, the central bank, yesterday cut interest
rates by 1 percentage point in response to data showing increased weakness
in the economy and evidence that monetary policy is achieving greater
financial stability, writes Philip Gawith in Johannesburg.
Mr Chris Stals, the bank's governor, said it would be lowering its benchmark
lending rate - the Bank rate - from 15 to 14 per cent.
The rate cut, the fourth since March 1991, had been widely discounted in the
money markets.
The average tender rate for Treasury Bills with a maturity of 91 days, for
example, declined from 13.38 per cent on July 3 to 12.16 per cent on
November 13.
Mr Stals cited sustained lower money supply and credit extension figures,
and the downward trend in producer and consumer price inflation (13.5 per
cent in September) as supporting a rate cut. He also referred to recent
figures suggesting real gross domestic product shrank at an annualised rate
of 5.7 per cent during the third quarter of the year.
