<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / International Company News: Petrobras president quits as
fuel price row surfaces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Benedito Moreira, president of Petrobras, the Brazilian state oil giant,
resigned yesterday along with his finance director after a dispute with Mr
Itamar Franco, Brazil's new president, over fuel prices.
The move came after a meeting in which Mr Franco again delayed approving
increases in fuel prices to keep up with inflation, now running at more than
26 per cent a month. Mr Moreira said last week that the company was losing
Dollars 10m per day because of the failure to make the usual monthly
adjustment for inflation.
Mr Moreira is not the first president of Petrobras to complain about the
government using fuel prices as a tool to repress inflation. Last year the
company - one of the largest in Latin America - made its first loss.
Mr Moreira first offered his resignation six weeks ago after the suspension
of President Fernando Collor amid a multi-million dollar corruption scandal.
He resubmitted it last week amid the furore over prices.
The company's new president is 54-year-old Mr Joel Mendes Renno from Mr
Franco's home state and a former president of Vale do Rio Doce, the state
mining company. He previously worked at Petrobras between 1981-1986 and will
be the company's sixth president in just two and a half years.
</TEXT>
