<DATE>921117
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Fears of delay to BR sell-off
spread to DoT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS THAT the privatisation of British Rail may be delayed have spread to
the Department of Transport.
Some people in the department believe the bill may not be published until
February. That would mean it would almost certainly not receive final
parliamentary approval until next October or November.
The setback has been caused by the postponement of debate on legislation
already before parliament, paving the way for privatisation of British Rail
and British Coal. The paving legislation would allow the two organisations
to prepare for being sold, for example by appointing advisers.
Until recently Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, maintained that
he intended to publish the rail privatisation bill this month in the hope of
winning royal assent next summer.
The sale of British Rail's freight operations would have started soon
afterwards and the franchising of passenger services was intended to start
in April 1994.
The rail and coal paving bill was due to be discussed in detail by the House
of Lords last month, but was put on hold because of the row over pit
closures. Even if it is brought back to the Lords before Christmas, it is
unlikely to be passed by parliament until late January.
The privatisation bill itself cannot be introduced until the paving bill has
been approved.
British Rail would welcome a delay to privatisation. Sir Bob Reid, BR
chairman, told the cross-party Commons transport committee earlier this
month that 'major questions' needed to be resolved before the plans went
ahead.
Mr Robert Adley, Tory chairman of the committee, has urged postponement of
the legislation to allow his committee time to study the government's
proposals.
One of the biggest uncertainties concerns the introduction of a system of
charging train operators for the use of railway tracks. Coopers &amp; Lybrand,
the accountants advising the government, have yet to produce its report on
the track access regime.
Many private-sector companies interested in running trains have said that
they cannot decide whether privatisation will prove attractive until they
have seen the Coopers &amp; Lybrand report.
Editorial Comment, Page 18
</TEXT>
