<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices led a general rally from morning lows at the London Metal
Exchange, but aluminium nickel and tin prices still finished down on the
day. Copper's early fall had found support, dealers said, and an upturn in
the afternoon was encouraged by a firmer tone for the metal on the New York
Commodity Exchange (Comex). Sterling's weakness made the crucial difference,
however, turning a Dollars 9 fall for three months metal into a Pounds
23.50-a-tonne rise from Friday's kerb (afterhours) close. ZINC followed
copper, but the market was thin as buyers disappeared at the first signs of
selling interest. At the close three months zinc was up only Dollars 6.50 on
the day at Dollars 1,045 a tonne and by the end of kerb trading it was
showing a Dollars 4 fall from the same point on Friday. NICKEL struggled to
maintain its rally, even after news of the expected setback to Cuba's 1992
production (see story above). Three months nickel closed on the LME at
Dollars 5,415 a tonne, down Dollars 82.50 from Friday.
Compiled from Reuters
