FT  17 NOV 92 / International Company News: Power Corp surges 30% on rise
from subsidiaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POWER CORP of Canada, the senior holding company of Mr Paul Desmarais, the
Montreal financier, unveiled a 30 per cent increase in nine-month net
profits.
The group lifted earnings to CDollars 135m (USDollars 107m), or CDollars
1.03 a share, up from CDollars 104m, or 77 cents a share, a year earlier on
revenues which edged ahead to CDollars 4.5bn from CDollars 4.47bn.
The subsidiaries, mainly in financial services and communications,
contributed CDollars 74.4m, against CDollars 70m.
Third-quarter net profits advanced 12 per cent to CDollars 32.3m, or 24
cents a share, on revenues marginally ahead at CDollars 1.47bn.
The results for both periods show that on an operating basis the
subsidiaries improved their performance.
At September 30, Power Corp and 70 per cent-owned Power Financial had
CDollars 750m cash and the group was virtually debt-free.
Its biggest subsidiaries are the publicly held Great West Lifeco, one of
North America's main life insurance companies, and Investors Group, a
financial services retailer.
Mr Desmarais, in a joint venture with the Frere family of Belgium, owns 57
per cent of Paresa, the European holding company controlling Petrofina and a
string of investments in Europe's industrial, financial services and
communications sectors.
Hydro-Quebec, the electric power utility fully owned by the Quebec
government, suffered a 13.5 per cent decline in profits to CDollars 343m in
the first nine months.
