FT  17 NOV 92 / International Company News: Bank cleared of favour claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FAY, Richwhite, the New Zealand merchant bank, was yesterday cleared by a
public inquiry of allegations that as a leading shareholder in Bank of New
Zealand (BNZ) it was granted favours relating an urgent NZDollars 42.5m
(USDollars 22.31m) loan it received from BNZ in 1990, writes Terry Hall.
At the time Fay, Richwhite held around 26.9 per cent of BNZ and was its
biggest shareholder, apart from the New Zealand government.
Both sold their combined 82.9 per cent holding to National Australia Bank
(NAB) last week.
The claims were made during investigations into BNZ's affairs between 1985
and 1990 when it faced financial disaster due to NZDollars 2.8bn of bad
debts.
The investigations followed accusations made in parliament by Mr Winston
Peters, a dissident government backbencher. Mr Peters and a dismissed BNZ
executive claimed Fay, Richwhite had used undue influence in getting a loan
to refinance its Auckland headquarters building, and it was in excess of the
BNZ's normal loan to value ratio.
Mr Larry Johnson, the BNZ executive, also claimed in an affidavit in
parliament he had been intimidated into approving the loan by Sir Michael
Fay, who was both a director of the BNZ, and joint managing director of Fay,
Richwhite.
