FT  17 NOV 92 / International Company News: Skoda completes external
refinancing for expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SKODA Automobilova, the Czech car maker in which Volkswagen is building a 70
per cent stake, has just completed the first significant external financing
of its revised 10-year, DM7bn (Dollars 4.6bn) expansion and modernisation
programme.
The DM1.4bn financing has been structured by the International Finance
Corporation (IFC), the private investment arm of the World Bank, with a
group of four commercial banks and the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (EBRD).
The IFC is responsible for raising DM600m of which it will retain DM200m,
with the rest going to commercial banks under the IFC umbrella. The four
lead banks, Dresdner, Deutsche Bank, J. P. Morgan and Credit Suisse First
Boston, are syndicating a further DM400m parallel loan. The EBRD is expected
to provide DM200m and syndicate DM200m to commercial banks, although the
EBRD board has not yet approved the operation.
Spreads on the current six to 12-year financing operation are said to be the
finest for a central European borrower and below the 2.5 per cent over Libor
at which Hungary has been able to borrow on international capital markets in
recent months.
