<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Amstrad holders 'unlikely to do better than
30p'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMSTRAD shareholders should accept the 30p-a-share buy-out offer made by Mr
Alan Sugar, Kleinwort Benson, financial adviser to the board of the computer
and electronics company he founded, has recommended in the offer document.
A report commissioned by Kleinwort from Touche Ross, Amstrad's auditor,
warned that in the event of the company considering a voluntary liquidation
shareholders would be unlikely to get materially more than 30p a share.
Amstrad's net asset value was 46.3p per share at its June 30 financial
year-end.
Shareholders should also vote for the offer because Amstrad depended on the
'expertise and motivation' of Mr Sugar, Kleinwort said in the document
posted yesterday.
Mr Sugar planned to use a loan from Amstrad to finance part of the Pounds
112.7m purchase of the 66 per cent of the shares he does not own. This
arrangement would be 'fair and reasonable' to shareholders, Kleinwort said.
The document made it clear that dividends from Amstrad, once it was wholly
owned by Mr Sugar, would help repay some of the loans used to finance the
buy-out.
If shareholders rejected the offer, there would be little prospect in the
near future of Amstrad paying 'a significant regular dividend', Mr Sugar
warned in the document.
If shareholders accept the offer, the price would represent an annual rate
of return of approximately 27.9 per cent for those who bought shares at
Amstrad's 1980 flotation and subsequently took up his rights at the time of
two scrip issues and a rights issue.
However, if a shareholder bought nil paid rights at the time of Amstrad's
rights issue and took up those rights, the annual rate of return reduces to
about 8.6 per cent.
Mr Sugar intends to turn Amshold, the Jersey holding company which he set up
for the buy-out, into one of his main vehicles. In addition to holding the
shares in Amstrad, it would hold Amprop, a property dealing company wholly
owned by Mr Sugar and members of his family, as well as Tottenham Hotspur,
in which he has a 47.8 per cent holding.
</TEXT>
